segments.text: Did he come in, as far as you know, with any kind of a blueprint, any kind of goals, a plan of action?
No, I think he did not.
He came right out of the College of Geosciences, where he had been doing a stellar job, but he hadn't been there but a year, as I recall.
He was here when the Senate, I mean, he worked well with Frank, and I certainly enjoyed working with him.
And so there was a pretty good team of like-minded folks who were concerned about continuing the forward motion of this institution.
Okay, let's please describe the other key folks.
Howard Vestal.
Howard went out about the time Mack did.
Okay.
And so Robert Smith.
But you worked with Howard for a while, didn't you?
Yes.
Oh, that's what I, how was he to work with?
Oh, wonderful.
He was a real easygoing guy.
I liked him.
I'm sure you did, too.
Oh, you bet.
Yeah.
John Coldis, Vice President for Students.
I had not...
a lot to do with John Coldis.
Typically, when there were cases involving students, I was sort of, the dean of faculty's office was the focal point for a student who had a complaint about
for sexual harassment reasons or whatever.
Well, for sexual harassment reasons.
And I never got involved with CODIS on something like that, really.
Did you ever have to deal with any serious sexual harassment?
Yes.
Can you describe the nature of any of them?
There were a couple of cases where it was male-male.

One, the faculty member had another job perking and went to that other job and I've talked to him since and to the best of my knowledge it was one of those borderline cases and if he transgressed then he apparently never did again.
There was another case that was really a sticky wicket where a professor
again with males, although he was married and everything else and had been for years.
But he, it was really a pretty open and shut case.
Did you ever have to deal with a case where a faculty member went through the whole hearing process
that might lead to termination?
Yes, but it didn't lead to termination, but he lost the case.
The girl didn't press any further.
She had already left.
She was brought back to appear.
It was messy.
There were quite a few of them actually, and they haven't diminished as I understand it from talking with Bill Perry.
It got increasingly difficult.
We had a couple of cases, in fact, after I had stepped down, retired, I was in a federal court in Galveston over an age discrimination case in architecture.
But we won that case.
The guy lost his own case by what he said before a jury.
What would you, let's make believe somebody said, well, what described the task of the dean of faculties?
What is the role of the dean of faculties?
People have asked my wife that, and she said, well, he runs a complaint department for the faculty.
I'm sort of an, I think, and you were too, an ombudsman.
Also, I think we served as linkages between groups that needed to get together sometimes for one reason or another.
I always felt that I was
counsel to faculty who needed some advice or some way of finding out how to get advice.
This sounds like I'm self-serving, but one of the most interesting cases I had, and I never met this person, was a black individual that had been hired in another part of the university.
He came here with his wife and newly adopted child and discovered that he could not get insurance for the adopted child without waiting.
It was either six months or a year.
And somebody said, call Phillips.
You're talking about under the university's insurance program?
Yes.
Health insurance.
And, you know, it's obviously common, sound public policy to encourage adoption.
And particularly, you know, in the black population, the problem is really quite serious of finding adoptive parents.
Well, I couldn't believe it.
I couldn't believe it.
I called Ray Smith.
And I heard, well, we've always done it.
What else are you going to hear from him?
But I said, well, this is just intolerable.
I said, this isn't a faculty member.
It's not my jurisdiction, but I'm so mad about it.
I'm going to route a letter through you to Frank.
And if you feel the way I do, I'd appreciate it if you'd sign it.
Otherwise, it's going to him anyway.
And I said, who the hell made this rule?
He said, well, it's the coordinating board.
Yeah.
I said, what have we got to do with it, Ray?
And he said, well, I don't know, but they did make that rule.
He said, they can have called meetings.
And as a matter of fact, he said, I think, and he looked at his appointment book, we're having a meeting next Monday.
This is like a Thursday.
He said, we're having a meeting on Monday.
I'll bring it up at that meeting and maybe they'll take some action.
And I said, well, okay, I'll give you to Monday evening.
Otherwise, you'll see my letter on Tuesday morning for your signature or not.
And he called me Monday afternoon and said, they changed the rule.
And I called the guy and told him that it's going to be changed, and I never heard anything more about it.
But can you imagine a silly-ass rule like that?
I never met the man.
I don't know who he was.
I can't remember his name.
Now, see if you agree with this description I sometimes used to use.
I used to say to people that at least part of the role of the dean of faculties was to be a spokesman for the faculty to the administration.
That's exactly right.
And vice versa.
And to, in some ways, be one of the deans, but on other days just be a member of the academic community.
Do you know where the title came from?
Plural, faculties.
No, I don't.
I always wondered, and sometime after I was at UTEP, I happened somehow to see an old Clemson College catalog.
And I looked in there, in the administration, and there's a man named Jack Kenny Williams,
whose title was Dean of Faculty.
And it was a title that had been, and he was the first one at Clemson.
And that was the

And the idea, as I understood it, was that there was a faculty in agriculture, a faculty in engineering, a faculty in arts and sciences, and so that he was the dean to represent all of those faculties.
And that's why the plural.
Because a few other places I've seen somebody who has the title dean of the faculty.
Yeah, and he may be the chief academic officer.
Right, right.
and certainly that would not have been fitting.
There was some association of dean of, I never joined it, don't know where.
Alright, surely you must have had some, share with the machine some goofy dean of faculty experiences.
Goofy.
Goofy, off the wall, I know you're not going to believe it type experiences.
Well, I'll have to think about that because I... Where some faculty member or dean wanted you to do something that was completely ridiculous or where you were given a report that was incredible?
Well, I do remember one that was unbelievable and it occurred in a certain college.
An accrediting committee came on campus
And after a couple of days of talking to everybody, they had their final meeting and typically I would meet with them.
So I sat down with them and they began by saying we had a remarkable faculty.
And I said, well, that's awfully good to know.
I'll be pleased to have that.
He said, but we're really reluctant about recommending accreditation.
And I said, why?
You just told me we had a good faculty, and you said we had a good program, blah, blah, blah.
Well, we think your faculty's so good that you're probably going to lose some of them.
Well, I thought I was listening to, and these were people that were from second-rate places.
That's what really pissed me off.
And I blew my stack.
I said, of course we're going to be rated, just like we rate good schools for high-class people.
If we don't get rated, there's something wrong with us.
I was just madder than hell.
Well, the chief board rejected their recommendation, but we were prepared, the dean and I were prepared to go, you know, ballistic over this.
And that was, talk about goofy, I think that was goofy.
You mentioned Phi Beta Kappa a while ago.
Was there a formal proposal while Vanderbilt was president?
Yeah.
There'd been one in my day.
Yes.
Somebody torpedoed it as I recall.

And one of the factors that helped to torpedo it is that two of the visiting team members were spinster ladies from women's colleges in the mid-Atlantic area, and they gave me the impression that they had gotten from somewhere well before they got here, that we were a good old boy
a redneck country bumpkin school, and we didn't have a chance.
Was there a visit, was there an on-campus visit from, you know, during the Vandiver days?
Well, if there was, I don't remember, remember meeting with it, so I guess it never did come to pass, but we did, we did try, and a chap that headed it up,
Frank personally asked him to do it, was a former head of the economics department who came from Tulane.
And I can't remember his name, but.
Because to me that's a very appropriate goal.
Yes.
Because if Baylor, SMU, TCU, Trinity, Rice, UT, A&M ought to be competitive.
I agree.
With that.
I agree.
Let's see, so we have Eaton and Mobley, I mean Eaton and Bill Mews.
Who follows when Mews leaves to go?
He was in the Chancellor's office from the business school, the Deputy Chancellor.
After Vandiver, who is the president?
Mobley?
Mobley.
Is that still in your day?
Yes, yes.
All right.
How did you learn that Vandiver was not going to be president anymore?
I think he told me that he said, I'm going to quit while I'm ahead.
Okay.
All right.
And then was there an interim or did Mobley come?
Mobley followed him.
Yeah.
Describe Mobley's management leadership style.
Well, he was not the kind that walked the floor of the faculty, of the factory, as Vannevar was.

he moved and I thought this was a mistake he moved and took the vice president for finance with him but not the provost that was symbolically bad and he moved over to the tower like I as an outsider thought oh this is isolating the president from the kind of camp easy accessibility
Yeah, I did too.
I thought it was a major mistake.
He was a disappointment to me.
I thought that apparently he had done a pretty good job as a dean, but apparently he just
Right.
Was he the president when you retired?
Yes.
Okay.
So those ten years, what were some of the high points for you?
Victories, joys?
The book that you have will sort of emphasize some of the things.
Working to

to assisting in the creation of the senate I think certainly was one the expansion of the development faculty development program which and I didn't tell you this but after we got money out of the former students then we took the case of the

department head dean who is stepping down and needs also needs to get and we've been using the development study program for those people but we went to the development office and said this would be an appropriate thing for you all to fund so they came up with a bunch of money for that which I felt was a good
For a while there, our effort to attract blacks was somewhat effective as long as we were paying the full salary, not only blacks but minorities.
I got some pleasure out of that.
The revision of the academic freedom and responsibility tenure policy, that was a massive effort.
involving, I worked closely with then legal office person Colleen Batchelor, Bill Batchelor's wife, who has worked for, what's his name, who was the attorney, chief attorney?
Jimmy Bond.
Jimmy Bond, who's now with the firm that, well, anyway, with a local firm.
That took, oh, a year or two to get the policy redone, then the procedures relating thereto.
I remember one of the deans saying, who had been a vice president at University of Houston, saying, if only we had had that at Houston, life would have been a lot simpler.
But Vandiver didn't like it.
He thought it was too detailed.
And I didn't like it, too.
This is one of the interesting, in some respects, I didn't.
One of the things that happens, it seems to me, when you're trying to write problems, trying to make procedures clear, you end up
inadvertently or inadvertently bureaucratizing things to a sometimes ridiculous point.
So Vandiver had something of a point there.
We were dealing with all kinds of conceivable possibilities, and we end up with a document that doesn't leave you much wiggle room, to use a term that
Gordon Eaton used to use a lot.
But anyway, all in all, I think it did help the faculty and that's what it was all about.
I mentioned earlier, I found it interesting that so many people came out of agriculture.
It was agriculture, for example, that first presented or asked for from the Senate a procedure whereby
it was laid out how to hire a department head, no more of this business of O.D.
Butler deciding who was going to be.
And then it went on for department head review and department and dean hiring and review.
So we developed a fairly elaborate procedure there too.
Other highlights and victories?
You know, we're making a tally now of the things that you're saying, yeah, I'm glad we did it.
We're able to get those done.
On a personal level, I really enjoyed the job on the standpoint of being able to study the various cultures of the colleges.
Fascinating to look at these different tribes and see what their rituals are and all of that.
and in the process meet an awful lot of fine folks.
A few pickles, but an awful lot of lovely people.
And I found that to be a good experience.
I'm not going to ask the negative now.
In your day, which of the programs do you think were most nationally competitive?
Of the various colleges or departments?
Colleges.
Geosciences has always been a class act.
Per capita, per faculty, they raise money like there's no tomorrow.
I always wanted the College of Science to sit in it, because every time they'll hire a chemist, I don't care how much money they bring in,
the cost of labs and all the rest of it that goes with it eats you up.
I'm told that Rutter picked two departments to be leading edges.
It might have been better if he'd picked something other than chemistry.
Economists are high priced, but you only need an economist.
You don't need a bloody lab with them.
Science certainly is strong.
If you look at where the distinguished professors are, they're concentrated in the College of Science.
I think education has really done rather well for itself.
Liberal arts certainly, I was upset when liberal arts slipped from second place to third when business overtook.
Business had been number two, then slipped to three, and then reclaimed two.
But I think a university, to be a really good university, has to have an enormously strong liberal arts college.
And so, that has certainly improved too, I have to say, enormously.
See, I really come out of liberal arts and economics.
I have a very bizarre history.
I would love to have been in the room when Earl Rudder gave Mel Greenhut a long lecture
about not bringing any liberal economists here, because I don't think Mel Greenhut would have needed that lecture.
No, he didn't need the lecture.
But he got it anyway because Rutter didn't know, apparently, that he was conservative by nature.
Any great frustrations of things that you wish
we could have done during that ten years?
I wish we could have done more with minority hiring, but given the community, the cards were stacked against us to some extent, and with student recruitment, too.
Now, there was no, on the campus, there were no roadblocks, were there?
No.
No, I think the community was more of the problem.
Vannevar really tried in that area, there's no question about that.
Coldest wasn't much help, by the way.
I think that... Let's see, and the Honors Program was really going well during those years under Dale Noble, wasn't it?
Yes.
Barry Shapiro got it started, and Dale Noble did a fine job.
Dale's now the president up at, I believe, Denison?
Denison, uh-huh.
One of the things I enjoyed doing was being sort of a mentor to Larry.
God, I tell you, when you get older, your names fade away.
Anyway, he went up to be a dean in Arkansas, and now is the vice president
in a school in Oregon and I kind of mentored him.
He had been in charge of the honors program for a couple years and then he left.
But while he was, he didn't have all that much to do and so he worked with me on the program like the academic freedom responsibility and tenure.
Can you think of any opportunities that in hindsight we didn't take?
Well, I can think, see mistakes we made in hiring deans, and I chaired them.
We could have progressed better if we'd found somebody who turned out to be more effective, but you know,
There's always a strong tendency for the faculty to want somebody from off the campus, figuring they can drive a better bargain and get more goodies for them.
And so you end up buying sometimes an unknown quantity.
Let me add to that.
I've always said too that search committees tend to over concentrate on the apparent strengths of the outsider.
never thinking about how much the outsider has to learn about the local situation.
And they then overemphasize the apparent shortcomings of the local person.
Because his warts are all there to be seen.
That's right.
Not realizing that they know all of those shortcomings and what their limits are.
And that the newcomer, if he or she has no experience in that region,
may spend the first year just settling in.

Whereas I've always thought, and I got this idea from Earl Rudder, that one of the tasks of every administrator ought to be to have an adjutant who might have the capability to move right on in and keep the ball rolling.
Can you think of some examples of where there was a notable
lack of continuity going from one administrator to the next?
Well, talking about presidents, I think there was a lack of continuity certainly between Sampson and Vandiver, but it didn't make any difference in that case.
All right.
And of course... Then from Vandiver to Mobley?
Although Vandiver stayed around, but I don't think Mobley ever asked his opinion on anything.
I don't think there's been any continuity since Williams ceased being president.
That's probably true.
There was none between Williams and Jarvis.
I've learned in interviewing Mrs. Williams that Rudder and Williams
were on the phone and did exchange some letters.
And the Rutter plan was Williams was going to come and in today's lingo be the executive vice president for the institution.
And Rutter was going to run the system.
His title would still be president.
But Williams, then when Mr. Rutter got sick and none of this was put into writing.
that it all was lost.
So there was some communication between the two of them, but since then it seems to me there's been a lot of break.
I don't think there was any problem when Gordon Eaton came in as vice president, academic vice president.
No.
That was a seamless transition.
Of course, I was already there.
That helped, I suppose, a little bit.
But he had hit it off well with Frank from the beginning.
You say he did?
He did, yes.
Now, I'm not aware of whether there was any conversation of meaningful nature between Calhoun and Prescott.
I don't think there was, but I'm not aware.
I'm not aware of it either.
We both were there, and I don't guess I
There is a tendency sometimes to ignore your predecessor.
The only time I ever asked, when I was acting dean, asked John Pearson something I wanted to know where some money had gone, and I found out that he had transferred it to the management department.
and that happened to be the department he went back to.
Let's see, system administration.
Did you ever deal with the system as dean of faculties?
Yes, this is something I had almost forgotten about, but when Hubert was chancellor, he instigated a program whereby we exchanged faculty
with preview and I was designated the person to go down and negotiate that.
Jerry Gaston was then head of sociology and a whole van load of us went down and the then president whose name I have forgotten let us cool our heels for an hour.
